<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp He looked at the piece of twisted steel in his hands. Many hard and long battles had it fought. Dubbed ‘Fyr’ by the one who had constructed it, engraved centuries ago when the sword was forged for his family. Time lost forever in its dulled shimmering blade. Now only a relic to hang on the walls of the castle Tyr Annon it would glow a warming red every time a possessor of magic would walk in the inner chambers of the castle, as if yearning to be fought with again. Text in Irhanje was inscribed on its blade by a smith before it was retired to the clutches of the 2 clasps on the wall “borne upon the noble family of Angellus”. Land of lands this sword had conquered and defended, only one of pure heart could wield it. Even though the castle’s scholars had said no one may ever use it again for the frail state it was in, it knew as well as the one who guarded it, that one day, it would be used, and break.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp He replaced the sword onto the wall and walked back through the inner chambers. Soon he would be at the castle gate, his horse waiting. Only one thing left to do before he left for the elvish kingdom of Wayward, get his sword. <br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp He stalked his way along the battlements of the castle, whisking from shadow to shadow. He met guards stationed at regular points, as were his orders and they parted their axes and pikes as he crossed in front of them. Up and down corridors, back and forth he weaved through the castle until he reached his own chambers. There upon the table at the side of the room laid a sword, simply crafted out of steel and iron. Nothing fancy on the hilt, no engraving on the blade. It’s the one that he had used since he had earned his knighthood those long years in this very keep.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp He grasped the blade hard, letting his own blood flow over the blade down onto the hilt. He then wiped it on a pure white cloth he left on the bed. Cleaning his hand in water and wrapping it in more of the pure white cloth, it stained immediately red and he tied it tightly, wincing a bit. He set off; down the spiral stairs into the courtyard. <br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp When he reached the castle gate his royal guard gave him his final salute before he set off into the country. They wore crimson and white, the colours of the castle. He tossed his cape over his shoulders and leapt onto his horse, probably never again to see the black gate, wooden drawbridge or even the sword of his family, ‘Fyr’. <br>
